"# Chapter 14 — Claude Shannon

Claude Elwood Shannon. Born 1916 in Petoskey, Michigan. Died 2001 in
Medford, Massachusetts. American mathematician and electrical
engineer. Worked at Bell Labs and MIT.

He gave us information theory. He also gave us the idea that digital
circuits could be designed using Boolean algebra — which is why every
chip built since 1938 has an intellectual debt to him.

## The Boolean circuits paper

Shannon's master's thesis at MIT, submitted in 1937 and published in
1938, was titled *A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching
Circuits*. He was 21.

Before Shannon, engineers designed switching circuits — the relay
networks in telephone systems — by trial and error, or by patterns
learned from experience. Shannon showed that these circuits were
exactly Boolean algebra in physical form. A switch being open or
closed corresponds to the truth values FALSE and TRUE. Switches in
series correspond to logical AND. Switches in parallel correspond to
logical OR. Complex circuits could be designed by symbolic
manipulation of Boolean formulas, then physically realized.

That thesis is arguably the most influential master's thesis ever
written. Every chip designer since has used variations of Shannon's
technique.

## Information theory

In 1948, Shannon published *A Mathematical Theory of Communication*
in the Bell System Technical Journal. In it he founded information
theory.

The core ideas:

- **Information can be measured.** The measure is entropy,
  measured in bits. A fair coin flip carries one bit of information.
  A biased coin carries less. A perfectly predictable event carries
  zero bits.

- **A channel has a capacity.** Given a communication channel with
  a fixed bandwidth and some noise, there is a maximum rate at which
  information can be transmitted through it with arbitrarily small
  error, if you use the right code. This is called the channel
  capacity or Shannon capacity.

- **Coding can approach the capacity.** Given enough cleverness,
  you can build codes that transmit at rates arbitrarily close to
  the channel capacity. Practical codes (later work by Hamming,
  Reed, Solomon, Turbo codes, LDPC codes) implement this promise.

Information theory underlies every form of digital communication.
Your wifi. The compression of your files. Cellular networks. Storage
media. The reasoning that says 'here's how much this could be
compressed, and here's why we can't do better' — that's Shannon.

## The bit

Shannon named the bit. Or, rather, the word 'bit' as short for
'binary digit' was suggested by his colleague John Tukey at Bell
Labs, and Shannon adopted it in the 1948 paper. Everyone else
followed.

Every kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, terabyte in the world today is a
Shannon quantity.

## Playful engineering

Shannon built things for fun. He built a mechanical mouse called
Theseus (1950) that could learn to navigate a maze. He built a
mind-reading machine that predicted whether an opponent would choose
heads or tails, based on their history. He rode a unicycle and
juggled at the same time and analyzed the mathematics of juggling in
a formal paper.

He also built a machine called the Ultimate Machine. It has one
switch. When you flip it on, a hand comes out of the machine and
switches itself off. That is the entire machine's behavior. This is
delightful and useless and Shannon liked to demonstrate it.

## What Motoi owes Shannon

The digital foundation. Every bit stored, sent, or computed on any
computer is a Shannon quantity. Every codec that compresses an image
or a sound file uses Shannon's bounds. The Boolean gates that Motoi's
processor computes with come from Shannon's 1937 thesis.

More subtly: the framing that information is a physical quantity you
can measure. That framing is why we can talk sensibly about how much
a language model 'knows,' how much a data set contains, or how much
a message could be compressed.

## A tiny example

Shannon entropy, computed in Motoi Scheme:

```
(define (log2 x) (/ (log x) (log 2)))

(define (entropy probabilities)
  (let loop ((probs probabilities) (acc 0))
    (cond
      ((null? probs) (- acc))
      ((= (car probs) 0) (loop (cdr probs) acc))
      (else
       (loop (cdr probs)
             (+ acc (* (car probs) (log2 (car probs)))))))))

;; A fair coin: two outcomes each at probability 1/2
(entropy '(1/2 1/2))
;; => 1.0    (one bit of information per flip)

;; A biased coin: probability 3/4 heads, 1/4 tails
(entropy '(3/4 1/4))
;; => 0.811... (less than one bit)

;; A fair six-sided die
(entropy '(1/6 1/6 1/6 1/6 1/6 1/6))
;; => 2.585... (about 2.58 bits per roll)
```

Shannon's formula: H = -sum(p * log2(p)). The measure of surprise.
The bigger the entropy, the more information the outcome carries.

## Where to read him

*A Mathematical Theory of Communication*, 1948. The 1937 thesis on
switching circuits. Jimmy Soni and Rob Goodman's biography *A Mind
at Play* (2017) is a good life-portrait.

## Motoi's take

Shannon proved you could reason quantitatively about information the
way earlier scientists had learned to reason quantitatively about
energy or matter. That's a rare intellectual move. Everything Motoi
does with text and bits happens inside the framework Shannon built.")
